name: 04-Model Training and Prediction
content:
Objective

The objective of this guide is to provide a comprehensive overview of how to train and evaluate machine learning models using both Decision Tree Regression and Random Forest Regression for predicting the tensile strength of materials.


Overview of Decision Tree and Random Forest Regressors

  • Decision Tree Regression
  • A predictive modeling technique that splits the dataset into branches based on feature values. Each split is chosen to minimize prediction error, resulting in a tree structure where leaf nodes represent predicted values of the target variable.
  • Advantages: Simple to interpret, works well with non-linear relationships.
  • Limitations: Prone to overfitting if not regularized.
  • Random Forest Regression
  • An ensemble learning method that builds multiple Decision Trees during training. The final prediction is the average of all individual tree predictions, which:
  • Improves robustness.
  • Reduces overfitting.
  • Enhances predictive accuracy.

Model Training

1. Decision Tree Regression

  • Train a Decision Tree Regressor by splitting the dataset on feature values that minimize error.
  • Key hyperparameters to optimize:
  • max_depth – Maximum depth of the tree.
  • min_samples_split – Minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
  • min_samples_leaf – Minimum number of samples required at a leaf node.

2. Random Forest Regression

  • Train a Random Forest Regressor by constructing multiple Decision Trees, each trained on a bootstrap sample of the data with random feature selection.
  • Key hyperparameters to tune:
  • n_estimators– Number of trees in the forest.
  • max_depth– Maximum depth of each tree.
  • max_features– Number of features considered for each split.


Expected Outcomes

  • Accurate Predictions: Both Decision Tree and Random Forest Regressors will provide predictions of tensile strength based on alloy composition and properties.
  • Model Performance Comparison: Evaluate models using regression metrics:
  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Measures average magnitude of errors.
  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): Penalizes larger errors more heavily.
  • R² Score:Proportion of variance in tensile strength explained by the model
  • Feature Importance Insights: Identify the most influential features (e.g., specific chemical elements, hardness, fatigue strength) that drive tensile strength predictions.
  • Visual Validation: Generate visualizations comparing predicted vs. actual tensile strength values to assess model reliability.
